  "summary": "While visiting the home of Colonel Melrose, the county's chief police officer, Mr. Satterthwaite receives a phone call from Constable Curtis informing the Colonel that James DeWitt has been found murdered in his study. The Colonel invites Satterthwaite to accompany him to Alder Road to investigate the case.\n\nAs they drive through the night, Satterthwaite recalls that the late Sir James was a stingy and angry man, while noting the beauty of Lady DeWitt. Colonel Melrose reveals that DeWitt was not poisoned but was beaten to death with a bronze statue. They discuss Paul de Longueville, a man rumored to have been expelled from the DeWitt residence a week earlier after allegedly making advances toward Lady DeWitt.\n\nTheir journey is interrupted by a minor car collision at a British crossroads. The driver of the other vehicle is identified as Mr. Harry Queene. Satterthwaite becomes extremely excited upon recognizing Queene, noting that they had previously met at a hotel called \"The Clock and Tweed.\" Satterthwaite informs the confused Colonel that Queene is a remarkable individual who previously solved the mysterious suicide of their friend, Derek Capel. Satterthwaite expresses his belief that their meeting at the crossroads was not an accident.",
